Germany, Year Zero
May 8th always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our small street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistor, would return from the Brandebourg prison.
I would no longer have to hide like after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of the month of February.
C’était le début d’une nouvelle vie.
Mais d’abord, il y a eu le chaos.
Les Nazis partis, les puissances d’occupation n’avaient pas encore mis en place d’administration.
Nous pillions les magasins du quartier. J’ai encore quelques volumes de poésie romantique récupérés dans une librairie.
J’avais seize ans. Les armées d’occupation se livraient à tous les excès.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was directly transported from his prison to the center of Berlin, and was charged - from nothing - with setting up the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was neither electricity, nor transportation, nor organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate question, although for our family it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But what for ?
For what future ?
“You must help,” my mother said to me.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the distribution of basic food supplies to several distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
J’avais une carte spéciale de “victime du fascisme”, tandis que d’autres arboraient une Croix de fer obtenue pour services rendus tardivement à l’armée.
Certains étaient des réfugiés de l’Est, beaucoup avaient vu leur maison détruite par des bombardements, presque tous pleuraient la disparition de proches.
Pourtant, cette étape n’a pas duré.
C’est pratiquement incroyable, mais trois ans plus tard, une réforme monétaire et des politiques libérales déclenchaient le “miracle économique” allemand.
Ou plus précisément, le miracle économique ouest-allemand.
The differences between occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and above all accompanied by a new form of servitude.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
On the other hand, after a short period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
A year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was not just an empty word, and it was based on German traditions.
Indeed, not everything was goodwill on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and everyone wanted to consolidate “their” part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of an economic nature, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy anchors itself unquestionably more easily in a context of economic revival.
This requires, above all, initiative from individuals who wish to end a period of hardship.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with initial capital.
Thus, the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
Similarly, the European Union has helped the former communist countries, and continues to support them in their efforts.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of the Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not begin its long journey by focusing on the past.
In fact, many have described the years of Adenauer after 1949 as a period of “restoration”, since too many minor Nazi figures remained in their positions.
In a certain way, the country ignored its past in order to move forward into the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany faced its past, with great success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other traumatized countries are therefore misleading.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to confront the past.
In the end, it is a better approach.
In Europe, May 8, 2005 is an occasion to look back with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
